  <h2>Why It Happens</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Restricted flow.</strong> When water can't move freely, trapped air escapes as a gurgle.</li>
    <li><strong>Venting issues.</strong> Plumbing vents help air balance; when they don't, drains can gurgle.</li>
    <li><strong>A filling or blocked system.</strong> Gurgling with slow drains can mean the tank or line needs attention.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to Act</h2>
  <p>
    An occasional gurgle with otherwise normal drains is worth noting; gurgling alongside slow drains, odors or wet spots is worth acting on. See <a href="/signs-a-septic-tank-may-be-full/">signs a tank may be full</a>, or <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> if the pattern continues.
  </p>

